Nested Classes in Java

A nested class is a class defined inside another class.

👉 Used to logically group classes and improve code organization.

Types of Nested Classes

There are 2 main types:

1. Static Nested Class
2. Non-static (Inner) Class
1. Static Nested Class

A static nested class is declared with the static keyword.

class Outer {
    static class Nested {
        void print() {
            System.out.println("Static nested class");
        }
    }
}
Creating object
Outer.Nested obj = new Outer.Nested();
obj.print();

👉 Key points:

does NOT need an instance of outer class
can access only static members of outer class
2. Inner Class (Non-static)

An inner class is connected to an object of the outer class.

class Outer {
    class Inner {
        void print() {
            System.out.println("Inner class");
        }
    }
}
Creating object
Outer outer = new Outer();
Outer.Inner inner = outer.new Inner();
inner.print();

👉 Key points:

needs outer class object
can access all members (including private) of outer class
Other Types of Inner Classes
3. Local Inner Class

Defined inside a method:

void method() {
    class Local {
        void print() {
            System.out.println("Local class");
        }
    }
}
4. Anonymous Class

Class without a name:

Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Anonymous class");
    }
};
Why use Nested Classes?
better code organization
logical grouping
encapsulation
cleaner code
Summary
nested class = class inside another class
types:
static nested
inner (non-static)
local
anonymous
used to structure code better
